  <item>
    <title>shitty digital detox guide</title>
    <description>A little guide on how to detox from social media and reclaim some of your free time
    </description>


    <summary><![CDATA[ 

<div class="parentboxcenter">
<hr>
  <h1> Intro  </h1>
<hr>
</div>

<div class="parentbox">



<img src="https://kerchunkleknoughts.github.io/mainblog/resources/images/floride.jpg" style="height:auto ; width: 500px;" > </img>

</div>

<div class="textcenter">
  <p class="betterp">
    As much as I love a good shitpost, I like every other person on the 
    face of the earth right now often find myself thinking that I spend 
    too much time online. Big whoop. Here I will share some techniques 
    that I've found that somewhat works at preventing me from 
    spending literally all of my free time on the internet. 

    I make no promises on this guides effectiveness, it works some days 
    and it doesn't other days. I will also be updating this guide as 
    I find better techniques. 



  </p>
</div>


<div class="parentboxcenter">
<hr>
  <h1> Delayed gratification method </h1>
<hr>
</div>

<div class="parentbox">



<img src="https://kerchunkleknoughts.github.io/mainblog/resources/images/cry.jpg" class="indicator3" > </img>

</div>


<br>

<div class="parentbox" >



<img src="https://kerchunkleknoughts.github.io/mainblog/resources/images/inpoint.png" class="fitcontentdiv" > </img>


<div class="textcenter" style="padding-left: 30px;">
  <p class="betterp">
    Uaehh I freaking love tumblr, and actually think that the time 
    I spend on it is sometimes well spent. The problem is when I 
    take it too far and browse it for an hour or more. 

    One of the main appeals I find comes from the absolutely 
    unhinged and bizarre posts that I don't find anywhere else. 

    Case in point to the left.

    So, my compromise with myself is to not go cold 
    turkey, but to set a tumblr time threshold. 
    Only at 6:00pm I allow myself to go online for like 
    20 minutes (yeah I set a timer), then, I get 
    back to doing other stuff. 

    That way, I still get a taste of online life, 
    and also don't feel like some type of phone 
    zombie. 



  </p>
</div>

</div>


<marquee behavior="scroll" direction="left" scrollamount="3" width="750px">

        <img src="https://kerchunkleknoughts.github.io/mainblog/resources/images/tf2.gif" class="indicatorp5"> </img>

</marquee>

<div class="parentbox" >


    <div class="textcenter" style="padding-right: 30px;">
  <p class="betterp">
    I am also experimenting with 
    moving more addicitive content (yt` shorts)
    to all the way to right before I 
    go to bed, with my timer set to 
    ten minutes. My philiosophy is that 
    since I am all doped out on melatonin, 
    I get too drowsy for it to become 
    a serious time sink, and I can easily turn it 
    off when I need to. Also at that point 
    I've already spent the whole day with 
    a higher level of dicipline, so it becomes 
    easier to shut things down.

    Basically, whenever I feel a craving to 
    go online, I can tell myself that I've 
    got phone in bed time later, and can 
    focus on other things. 



  </p>
</div>


<img src="https://kerchunkleknoughts.github.io/mainblog/resources/images/eepy.jpg" class="fitcontentdiv" > </img>



</div>





<div class="parentboxcenter">
<hr>
  <h1> Pavlov had a point maybe</h1>
<hr>
</div>

<br>

<div class="parentbox">
<img src="https://kerchunkleknoughts.github.io/mainblog/resources/images/pav.jpg" class="fitcontentdiv" > </img>



    <div  style="padding-left: 30px;">
  <p class="betterp">
    Another method I've deployed to stay productive, 
    is to form a pavlovian association with 
    dressing nice and being busy. Every time I 
    get working on schoolwork, I put on my
    </p>
    <p style="font-family: fantasy;">
      ✨ fancy trowsers✨</p> 
    <p class="betterp">  
    and a nice regular ass shirt (no metal tshirts).  
    To be honest, I have no idea if this actually works, but 
    you know what they say, if it aint broke don't 
    fix it!
        </p>  


</div>

</div>


<div class="parentboxcenter">
<hr>
  <h1> HOLY MANGA STRAT</h1>
<hr>
</div>

<br>



<div class="parentbox">


    <div class="textcenter" style="padding-right: 30px;">
  <p class="betterp">
      I tend to get a little nervious 
      when I am sitting somewhere in public 
      and need to pass the time in a room full 
      of people. Now a social person would 
      turn to their neighbor and strike up 
      a conversation and make lifelong 
      friends and ride off into the sunset with a 
      billion dollars, but thats not how I roll baby. 

      Instead, I found the way to not give in to the 
      temptation of slushifying my mind with social media
      right then and there is to just read manga on my phone. 

      You can find just about any manga online for <a href="https://mangakatana.com/"> free</a>
      so long as you pair it with a good mobile ad block. 

      I usually use firefox with this <a href="https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/adblock-for-firefox/">extension</a>
    </p>



</div>


<div class="parentbox">
<img src="https://kerchunkleknoughts.github.io/mainblog/resources/images/veg.jpg" class="fitcontentdiv" style="height:200px;" > </img>
</div>

</div>





<div class="parentboxcenter">
<hr>
  <h1> TIMERS!</h1>
<hr>
</div>


<div class="parentboxcenter">
<img src="https://kerchunkleknoughts.github.io/mainblog/resources/images/rabb.webp" class="indicator2" > </img>
</div>



<br>

<div class="parentbox">




    <div  style="padding-left: 30px;">
  <p class="betterp">
      Its been said and done before, but I like 
      to set a timer for some amount of work 
      before I start the day, and whenever I
      get through an hour I pause the timer and 
      take a break. Uhh the only problem with 
      this system is sometimes I feel bad for 
      not working for as long as the timer 
      was set to. 
    </p>
  


</div>

</div>







    

<br><br>



<div class="parentboxcenter">
<hr>
  <h1> Conclusion?</h1>
<hr>
</div>





<br>

<div class="parentbox">




    <div  style="padding-left: 30px;">
  <p class="betterp">
      Thats the end maybe? If I find anything else that helps, 
      I'll update this guide again and post it. 

      thanks for reading!
    </p>
  


</div>

</div>
 ]]> </summary>

